Based on the gathered information, coarse tremors of the tongue are indeed observed in conditions such as Parkinson's disease, alcohol withdrawal delirium, thyrotoxicosis, and possibly in other neurological diseases like von Economo encephalitis or spinocerebellar ataxias. However, the primary hallmark of thyrotoxicosis involves fine resting tremors predominantly in the hands rather than coarse tremors affecting speech-related muscles. While coarse tongue tremors could theoretically appear in complex neurological scenarios like von Economo encephalitis or spinocerebellar ataxias, these are relatively rare occurrences outside specialized contexts. Given that coarse tongue tremors are more frequently documented in conditions unrelated to thyroid function—such as Parkinson's disease or certain forms of cerebellar degeneration—they serve as strong indicators pointing away from thyrotoxicosis unless otherwise specified. Therefore, despite the nuanced spectrum of possibilities highlighted by the evidence, thyrotoxicosis remains distinctly separate from the list of options provided, reinforcing the initial conclusion made earlier. My stance has remained unchanged since there continues to be no compelling evidence linking coarse tongue tremors definitively to thyrotoxicosis. \boxed{C}
